THE RISK:
{
 "id": "bundling-eliminates-bakeoffs-year1",
 "title": "Incumbent power-train bundling means the standalone PDU bake-off the 3% ramp assumes rarely happens",
 "narrative": "The 3% Year-1 obtainable factor implicitly assumes the venture gets evaluated: a buyer runs a PDU selection, the venture competes, and wins its share. But the growth capacity the 9% CAGR is made of — new builds and major fit-outs — buys rack PDUs inside integrated packages from Schneider, Vertiv, Eaton and Legrand, who can price the PDU line at near-zero margin inside busway + rack + UPS + cooling bundles worth orders of magnitude more. In those deals there is no PDU bake-off to enter. The corpus's own evidence already screams this: the generic 1–5% band is contradicted by every concrete datapoint found — a worked example at ~0.1% of SAM, and a real industrial-hardware entrant (Tractian) starting at ~0.001% of its market. The 3% mid-band survived because it was framed as 'already revised down from 6%' — a conservatism that is only conservative against fantasy.",
 "category": "competitive",
 "targetNodes": [
  "obtainableFactor"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "The five to seven vendors named as market leaders (Schneider, Eaton, ABB, Legrand, Vertiv, Siemens, Tripp Lite) all sell PDUs as one line inside a ~$23B power-equipment layer of integrated DC fit-out packages, enabling near-zero-margin PDU pricing within bundles",
   "refs": [
    "digest:cr3-vendors#c6",
    "digest:cust-mix#c2",
    "ledger:shape.cr3"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "New-build and fit-out capacity — where market growth concentrates — is specified as a package, so standalone PDU evaluations exist mainly in retrofit/replacement sockets; every concrete Year-1 datapoint in the corpus (TryBuildCo ~0.1% of SAM, Tractian ~$200K against a $14.9B market) lands one to three orders of magnitude below the generic 1–5% band, and one source frames SOM as a 3–5 year window, not Year 1",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:shape.cagr",
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c5",
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c6",
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c4"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "obtainableFactor 0.03 assumes access to competitive evaluations across the whole SAM; restricted to the standalone-evaluation slice with hardware-entrant win rates, the realistic Year-1 pace is ≤0.5% of SAM, cutting YAM by roughly five-sixths",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:obtainableFactor",
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c8"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The 3% carries the halo of a downward revision (from 6%) and sits mid-band of two cited benchmarks — it looks like the conservative choice that has already been challenged once. What hides the risk is that both benchmarks are generic startup heuristics; the sector-specific question 'in what fraction of CE PDU spend does a standalone evaluation even occur?' is never asked by a percentage-of-SAM framing.",
 "expectedObviousness": "medium",
 "falsifier": "In the first two quarters, ≥2 CE opportunities at operators reach a standalone PDU bake-off (venture invited, incumbent bundle displaced or absent) — or a bottom-up pipeline model (reps × win-rate × cycle time) that independently supports ≥3% of SAM in 12 months.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.55,
  "rationale": "The contradiction is already documented in the corpus: every concrete observed Year-1 datapoint sits far below the 1–5% band, and bundle-selling by integrated power vendors is standard; uncertainty remains on how much CE retrofit demand buys PDUs standalone [evidence revision: The load-bearing bundling premise is strongly corroborated by multiple vendor reference designs embedding PDUs in integrated packages, raising confidence in the mechanism. But the falsifying search also produced concrete standalone PDU tenders, confirming that standalone evaluations persist (as the hypothesis itself concedes) rather than being absent. These offset: stronger mechanism evidence balanced against demonstrated existence of standalone sockets. Net likelihood held at 0.55.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.55
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "obtainableFactor",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.005,
   "note": "Year-1 pace re-anchored to observed hardware-entrant base rates on the standalone-evaluation slice, not the generic 1–5% heuristic"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Fraction of addressable Year-1 opportunities where rack PDUs are specified standalone vs inside an integrated fit-out package",
   "where": "CE colo/enterprise fit-out tender documents and the venture's CRM opportunity coding",
   "threshold": "<30% of qualified opportunities are standalone PDU purchases",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Incumbent commentary on integrated-solution attach rates and rack-system bundling",
   "where": "Vertiv and Schneider quarterly earnings calls; product-launch materials for integrated rack/power-train offerings",
   "threshold": "Explicit strategy statements on selling rack power as part of integrated systems, with PDUs positioned as an attach line",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Replace the percentage heuristic with a capacity model built from the first 90 days of CE outreach: standalone-RFQ density × win rate × cycle time × fulfillment capacity",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "obtainableFactor",
   "note": "The corpus explicitly recommends this method over percentage heuristics; 90 days of pipeline data converts the node from folklore to measurement"
  },
  {
   "action": "Target retrofit and replacement RFQs — where PDUs are bought standalone and bundle pricing has no leverage — as the entire Year-1 focus",
   "type": "operational",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": null
  },
  {
   "action": "Get spec'd as the named alternate PDU in integrator and consulting-engineer BOM templates, so bundled deals carry an entry point",
   "type": "strategic",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": null
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "corroborated",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "Vertiv 360AI High Density Reference Design #026",
